{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17510582","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17510582"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:31:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:31:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11596"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11596","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11596"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.59,0.19,0.05,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4223"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103846"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4223","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4223"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11596"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86271"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"156"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"2308"},{"type":"tags","id":"2453"},{"type":"tags","id":"4923"},{"type":"tags","id":"10932"},{"type":"tags","id":"12909"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5554"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5556"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35903"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36817"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37053"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103846","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103846"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a five-day history of fever, chills, myalgia and headache. He normally suffers from migraines, however, this headache was more painful. He reports experiencing sinusitis two weeks ago that is not fully resolved. He had no prior sick close contacts and no past sexually transmitted infections. His vaccinations are up to date. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, he appears unwell with pulse rate 96/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 39\u00b0C. His Glasgow Coma Scale is 15 and he is oriented to time and place. Neurological examination revealed neck stiffness with limited range of motion. Knee extension on a flexed hip is limited due to pain. The remainder of the neurological examination is unremarkable. He has no skin rash. Blood cultures and lumbar puncture are performed.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["IV acyclovir and hydrocortisone","IV benzylpenicillin, dexamethasone, and ceftriaxone","IV dexamethasone and ceftriaxone","IV ceftriaxone alone","IV benzylpenicillin and ceftriaxone"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with the classic triad of bacterial meningitis: fever, headache, and neck stiffness. The positive Kernig\u0027s sign (limited knee extension on flexed hip due to pain) further supports this diagnosis. Given the recent sinusitis, this suggests possible pneumococcal meningitis with direct spread from the sinuses. Immediate empirical treatment is crucial and should not be delayed for diagnostic confirmation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIV benzylpenicillin, dexamethasone, and ceftriaxone\u003C/strong\u003E represents the most comprehensive initial treatment. Benzylpenicillin is essential because \u003Cem\u003EListeria monocytogenes\u003C/em\u003E is intrinsically resistant to cephalosporins, and this patient is at risk of \u003Cem\u003EL. monocytogenes\u003C/em\u003E infection as he is older than 50 years. Ceftriaxone provides broad-spectrum coverage against common bacterial meningitis pathogens, and dexamethasone reduces inflammation and improves neurological outcomes when given before or with the first dose of antibiotics.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIV dexamethasone and ceftriaxone\u003C/strong\u003E provides appropriate corticosteroid and antibiotic therapy but lacks the essential benzylpenicillin coverage for \u003Cem\u003EListeria monocytogenes\u003C/em\u003E, which is particularly important in patients over 50 years of age who are at increased risk of this infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIV acyclovir and hydrocortisone\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate for viral encephalitis, particularly herpes simplex encephalitis. However, this patient\u0027s presentation is more consistent with bacterial meningitis, and hydrocortisone has inferior cerebrospinal fluid penetration compared to dexamethasone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIV ceftriaxone\u003C/strong\u003E alone provides antibiotic coverage but lacks both the corticosteroid therapy that improves outcomes and the essential benzylpenicillin coverage for \u003Cem\u003EListeria monocytogenes\u003C/em\u003E in this age group.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIV benzylpenicillin and ceftriaxone\u003C/strong\u003E provides excellent antibiotic coverage including \u003Cem\u003EListeria\u003C/em\u003E coverage but omits the crucial corticosteroid therapy that has been shown to reduce mortality and neurological sequelae in bacterial meningitis when administered early.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["In cases of suspected bacterial meningitis, IV dexamethasone and empirical antibiotics i.e. ceftriaxone must be administered within the first hour or as soon as possible upon presentation.","Benzylpenicillin should be added to cephalosporin therapy for patients over 50 years due to risk of Listeria monocytogenes infection, which is intrinsically resistant to cephalosporins.","Dexamethasone improves neurological outcomes in bacterial meningitis when given before or with the first dose of antibiotics."],"references":["Van de Beek D, de Gans J, Spanjaard L, et al. Clinical features and prognostic factors in adults with bacterial meningitis. N Engl J Med 2004; 351:1849. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/15509818/","Pace D, Pollard AJ. Meningococcal disease: clinical presentation and sequelae. Vaccine 2012; 30 Suppl 2:B3. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22607896/","Carter E, McGill F. The management of acute meningitis: an update. Clin Med (Lond). 2022 Sep;22(5):396-400. doi: 10.7861/clinmed.2022-cme-meningitis. PMID: 36507811; PMCID: PMC9594998. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9594998/","Young N, Thomas M. Meningitis in adults: diagnosis and management. Intern Med J. 2018 Nov;48(11):1294-1307. doi: 10.1111/imj.14102. PMID: 30387309. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30387309/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86271"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11596"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86271","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86271"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-27T17:31:32+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-27T17:31:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4223"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103846"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"dat